(12701, 'I also like to look at the dynamic that takes place between religion and science because in a way both are asking the same questions: Who are we? Where do we come from? Why are we here? Where are we going? The methodologies are diametrically opposed but t', 'J. Michael Straczynski', 'science'),
(12702, 'Computer science is no more about computers than astronomy is about telescopes.', 'Edsger Dijkstra', 'science'),
(12703, 'Science is built up of facts as a house is with stones. But a collection of facts is no more a science than a heap of stones is a house.', 'Henri Poincare', 'science'),
(12704, 'Science is the knowledge of consequences and dependence of one fact upon another.', 'Thomas Hobbes', 'science'),
(12705, 'Inspiration in Science may have to do with ideas but not in Art. In art it is in the senses that are instinctively responsive to the medium of expression.', 'Arthur Erickson', 'science'),
(12706, 'No science is immune to the infection of politics and the corruption of power.', 'Jacob Bronowski', 'science'),
(12707, 'Indeed in view of its function religion stands in greater need of a rational foundation of its ultimate principles than even the dogmas of science.', 'Muhammad Iqbal', 'science'),
(12708, 'Yet higher religion which is only a search for a larger life is essentially experience and recognized the necessity of experience as its foundation long before science learnt to do so.', 'Muhammad Iqbal', 'science'),
